WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.440 --> 00:00:02.300
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Welcome to
the National Book Festival.

00:00:02.300 --> 00:00:05.350
My name is Rumaan Alam, i"m an
editor at the New York Times,

00:00:05.350 --> 00:00:07.230
and it is such a
pleasure to be here.

00:00:07.230 --> 00:00:08.820
I was saying to one of the --

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:10.920
one of the women working
the event that I've been

00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:12.710
to a lot of book festivals.

00:00:12.710 --> 00:00:15.160
And I expected something
really sedate and quiet

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:18.310
with like a few -- a few old
ladies with tote bags walking

00:00:18.310 --> 00:00:22.650
down the hall, and it's
like Black Friday out there.

00:00:22.650 --> 00:00:25.370
Which is an amazing -- which
is testament to what kind

00:00:25.370 --> 00:00:27.540
of a literary city
Washington D.C. is.

00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:30.760
And so, I'm really happy to be
here, and it's really a pleasure

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:32.840
to share the stage
with Sujatha Gidla,

00:00:32.840 --> 00:00:35.820
who has written a beautiful book
called Ants among Elephants:

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:39.660
An Untouchable Family and
the Making of Modern India.

00:00:39.660 --> 00:00:42.250
I have a million
questions for Sujatha,

00:00:42.250 --> 00:00:44.090
and I'm sure you will as well.

00:00:44.090 --> 00:00:46.520
So, about fifteen minutes
before we wrap up, I'll open it

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:48.470
up to questions from
the audience.

00:00:48.470 --> 00:00:50.950
But we're going to begin by
listening to Sujatha read

00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:53.620
from her book and then I'm
going to drive her crazy

00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:56.310
with a million questions,
so, please.

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:58.160
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Hi everybody.

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:01.120
So, the book is Ants
among Elephants,

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:04.430
this is my family
biography that intersects

00:01:04.430 --> 00:01:07.060
with the you could
say biography India --

00:01:07.060 --> 00:01:09.180
of India, Independent India.

00:01:09.180 --> 00:01:12.770
And I want to start with the --

00:01:12.770 --> 00:01:16.710
this section that
describes my uncle's wedding.

00:01:16.710 --> 00:01:22.090
He was 25, 24 years old and
the wedding is taking place

00:01:22.090 --> 00:01:25.150
in a village, and this is

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:29.510
about the preparation
of the wedding feast.

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:32.350
In fact, somebody
actually, you know,

00:01:32.350 --> 00:01:36.580
suggested that I send this
excerpt to Food and Wine.

00:01:36.580 --> 00:01:38.010
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: You should
-- oh, is this about the pig?

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:39.310
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:01:39.310 --> 00:01:40.610
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Yes,
you should, you should.

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:41.910
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: And it --
they would have been like,

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:43.290
really horrified [inaudible].

00:01:43.290 --> 00:01:44.590
So, all right.

00:01:44.590 --> 00:01:49.780
"On the morning of the wedding
Majula was walking by loud cries

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:52.920
from the alley next to here
uncle Galea's[Phonetic] house

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:54.370
in Sankarapuram .

00:01:54.370 --> 00:01:57.410
She sat up in fright and
started praying, "Oh,

00:01:57.410 --> 00:02:00.350
David, Jesus, Lord save us!"

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:04.090
A cousin of hers sitting
nearby put her sari end

00:02:04.090 --> 00:02:06.680
to her mouth to hide her smile.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:07.980
What, papa?

00:02:07.980 --> 00:02:11.620
No need to be scared,
they're just chasing the pig."

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:14.070
When Presenadro[Phonetic]
announced his son's wedding

00:02:14.070 --> 00:02:16.670
to the village, everyone
started drooling

00:02:16.670 --> 00:02:18.100
at that thought of the pig.

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:21.840
A wedding in an untouchable
colony is a festival,

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:24.820
and at the center of the
festival is the feast.

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:28.550
At -- and at the center
of the feast is the pig.

00:02:28.550 --> 00:02:31.830
As soon as a match is fixed,
both the bride's house

00:02:31.830 --> 00:02:36.050
and the groom's house get
hold of a piglet by buying one

00:02:36.050 --> 00:02:39.570
in an untouchable market
or catching a stray.

00:02:39.570 --> 00:02:43.160
For weeks the families raise
their pigs with great care.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:46.760
A wedding pig is
no ordinary pig,

00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:49.030
it must be be treated
with respect.

00:02:49.030 --> 00:02:51.790
No one is allowed to
talk harshly to it,

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:53.660
even if it should get n the way.

00:02:53.660 --> 00:02:57.850
"Hey, watch your mouth,
that's the wedding pig!"

00:02:57.850 --> 00:03:00.400
The families feed it
as well as they can,

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:04.120
giving it starch water left
after rice is cooked to drink,

00:03:04.120 --> 00:03:06.570
or sometimes even [inaudible].

00:03:06.570 --> 00:03:10.840
Most untouchable families don't
have that kind of food to spare.

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:14.800
And the best thing about a pig
is that it can feed itself.

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:19.790
The staple for pigs in India
is what's delicately called --

00:03:19.790 --> 00:03:21.090
filth.

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:22.620
They eat human shit.

00:03:22.620 --> 00:03:24.360
If the [inaudible]
family it too poor

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:27.410
to feed their pig,
it's not a big deal.

00:03:27.410 --> 00:03:30.260
The pig simply goes around
the village eating shit

00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:33.340
and gets just as fat.

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:37.880
Untouchables will often
marvel, shit it may beat,

00:03:37.880 --> 00:03:41.460
but a pig's meat is the
sweetest meat of all.

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:45.760
But the announcement of
[inaudible]'s wedding meant more

00:03:45.760 --> 00:03:48.220
than just the prospect of pig.

00:03:48.220 --> 00:03:50.610
Presenadro had risen
above the condition

00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:53.810
of all those he left
behind in Sankarapuram .

00:03:53.810 --> 00:03:56.220
He was a teacher not a farmhand.

00:03:56.220 --> 00:03:58.620
He had lived in cities
and towns.

00:03:58.620 --> 00:04:00.860
He interacted with Caste people,

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:04.820
with other educated
people, people with jobs.

00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:08.150
In the eyes of the villagers
he was a -- he was wealthy.

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:11.400
He owned four and a
half acres of land.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:13.580
His son was the first ever to --

00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:17.160
first ever college going
man from the village.

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:20.000
And now that -- not the eldest

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.170
and favorite son was getting
married, there would be a lot

00:04:24.170 --> 00:04:27.930
of pork at this feast.

00:04:27.930 --> 00:04:31.690
[inaudible] might even
get a pig that -- of --

00:04:31.690 --> 00:04:35.150
pig of that exotic new breed.

00:04:35.150 --> 00:04:37.580
Only a year or two earlier,

00:04:37.580 --> 00:04:40.570
a new breed of pig had
arrived in the country.

00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:41.870
They're known

00:04:41.870 --> 00:04:44.380
as Semapundalu[Phonetic]
European pigs,

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:46.540
they come from Russia.

00:04:46.540 --> 00:04:50.100
Some call them red pigs
because their skin is pink

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:52.320
and hairless, and smooth.

00:04:52.320 --> 00:04:56.790
They're raised on farms in pens
not like loose in the streets.

00:04:56.790 --> 00:05:00.680
They're fed a calibrated diet
and grow many times fatter

00:05:00.680 --> 00:05:03.000
and larger than Indian pigs.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.870
In fact, they seem to
have nothing in common

00:05:05.870 --> 00:05:09.540
with the black, hairy,
filthy native pigs.

00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:13.670
But, whenever some -- whenever
anyone tries to raise one

00:05:13.670 --> 00:05:16.190
of these foreign
pigs on his own,

00:05:16.190 --> 00:05:19.190
pretty soon it loses
its caste and turns

00:05:19.190 --> 00:05:22.390
into an ordinary Indian pig.

00:05:22.390 --> 00:05:27.920
It's pink turning to black, it's
fat shrinking away as it runs

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:30.080
through the street
wallowing in sewers

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:33.350
and swallowing the effluvium.

00:05:33.350 --> 00:05:35.230
Everyone in Sankarapuram
looked forward

00:05:35.230 --> 00:05:38.880
to tasting a European pig
at [inaudible]'s wedding.

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:42.330
But, Presendra[Phonetic] had --

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:45.680
Presendra's[Phonetic]
son had other ideas.

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:50.950
When the matter of the pig came
up it pained Satyam[Phonetic]

00:05:50.950 --> 00:05:54.790
that his relatives were so
different from his cast friends.

00:05:54.790 --> 00:05:56.230
He had attended many

00:05:56.230 --> 00:05:59.400
of his friend's weddings
while living in Gurdwara.

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:01.280
And except for
Nyteria[Phonetic],

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:03.580
none of them had served meat.

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:06.910
Meat is believed by
Hindus to be impure.

00:06:06.910 --> 00:06:10.550
Brahmins the purest
caste, eat no meat at all,

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:12.860
not even fish or eggs.

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:17.870
Untouchables, being impure
themselves eat even carian[beef]

00:06:17.870 --> 00:06:20.190
the flesh of cows that drop dead

00:06:20.190 --> 00:06:23.200
by the roadside of
age or disease.

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:25.330
Which, since cows are sacred

00:06:25.330 --> 00:06:29.570
and cannot be slaughtered is
the only kind of beef that falls

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:32.870
to human consumption
under Hindu law.

00:06:32.870 --> 00:06:38.680
Middle caste except for merchant
caste eat meat but never beef.

00:06:38.680 --> 00:06:42.000
And it is inauspicious
to serve any meat at all

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.250
at births, funerals, or wedding.

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:48.820
Satyam[Phonetic] considered it
uncultured and even barbaric

00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:52.400
to eat the flesh of a
pig on any occasion.

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:56.230
A pig to a caste Hindu
is a symbol of filth.

00:06:56.230 --> 00:06:59.860
Untouchables are commonly
associated with two creatures,

00:06:59.860 --> 00:07:02.670
the craw -- the crow
for its blackness

00:07:02.670 --> 00:07:05.130
and the pig for its foulness.

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:08.930
When people assembled under the
Banyan tree to plan the feast,

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:13.290
Satyam[Phonetic] told them
there would be no pig.

00:07:13.290 --> 00:07:15.670
The elders took the
cigars out of their mouths.

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:16.970
"What? What?

00:07:16.970 --> 00:07:19.530
A wedding feast with no pig?"

00:07:19.530 --> 00:07:22.840
Satyam[Phonetic] replied,
There won't beany meat."

00:07:22.840 --> 00:07:24.680
They couldn't believe
their ears.

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:28.130
The most fabulous that they
would ever attend was turning

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:32.430
out to be the worst
one they ever heard of.

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:34.750
They wanted nothing
to do with it.

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:38.500
Men, women, and children turned
and went home disappointed,

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:41.480
but Satyam[Phonetic]
was unmoved.

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:42.780
Discussion of the village --

00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:45.390
discussion in the village
went on for several days.

00:07:45.390 --> 00:07:48.330
In the end, the elders
came to Presendro[Phonetic]

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:53.930
with a proposal, "How about a
pig for the village and hens

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:56.230
for the having red people?"

00:07:56.230 --> 00:07:59.540
that is educated people,
the educated ones.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:01.320
Satyam[Phonetic] said, "Never!"

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:03.050
Presendro[Phonetic]
took his son's side,

00:08:03.050 --> 00:08:05.910
"He has stopped eating beef
in [inaudible] when had

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:10.060
to hide his caste for the sake
of being allowed to rent a room

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:12.230
in the house of a
caste in the family."

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:16.240
And now, the very thought of
beef was revolting to him.

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:17.900
He didn't mind pork himself,

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:20.610
but he could understand
how his son felt.

00:08:20.610 --> 00:08:23.750
Instead of a pig, he had
bought sacks of vegetables

00:08:23.750 --> 00:08:26.700
and from some kamas[Phonetic],
whose children he taught

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:28.000
in Thalipuru[Phonetic],

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.790
some strange upper
caste flour based foods,

00:08:31.790 --> 00:08:33.680
uperdums[Phonetic]
and ladus[Phonetic].

00:08:33.680 --> 00:08:39.090
The villagers decided to boycott
the wedding all together.

00:08:39.090 --> 00:08:41.970
One thing saved the day,
neither Presendro[Phonetic] nor

00:08:41.970 --> 00:08:45.010
Satyam[Phonetic] had a say in
what the bride's family could

00:08:45.010 --> 00:08:47.520
or could not serve
at their feast

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:49.310
on the night of the wedding.

00:08:49.310 --> 00:08:51.260
Everyone knew
Kadumarah[Phonetic] had already

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:54.620
been raising a pig for
the last few weeks.

00:08:54.620 --> 00:08:56.390
Whether Kadumarah
bought the pig --

00:08:56.390 --> 00:08:59.390
bought his big or caught
it himself was not clear,

00:08:59.390 --> 00:09:02.060
but it was a black Indian pig.

00:09:02.060 --> 00:09:04.970
That was the pig the young men
of the village were chasing

00:09:04.970 --> 00:09:06.630
on the morning of the wedding

00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:09.800
when they woke Majula
with their cries.

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:15.200
Majula went out to watch the
agile young men armed with long,

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:18.970
thick sticks, and clenching
cigars between their molars,

00:09:18.970 --> 00:09:22.180
running through the village,
loin clothes pulled tight

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:25.220
over their crotches and
between their buttocks,

00:09:25.220 --> 00:09:28.110
their bodies shiny with sweat.

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:30.100
One carried a special net.

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:34.710
The children of the village, 20,
30 of them naked, dust coated,

00:09:34.710 --> 00:09:36.940
wild haired, runny nosed.

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.760
The girls among them
also all naked,

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:43.250
but for their snail shell
anklets and the little silver

00:09:43.250 --> 00:09:48.400
or copper disks strung
around their waists

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:50.490
to preserve their modesty.

00:09:50.490 --> 00:09:52.410
They ran along the hunters.

00:09:52.410 --> 00:09:55.790
Everyone was screaming as
loud as he or she could.

00:09:55.790 --> 00:09:58.480
And the pig was screeching
even louder.

00:09:58.480 --> 00:10:01.480
Wild with fear, it
whizzed passed the house

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:05.850
like a cannonball, desperate
to escape the murderous youths.

00:10:05.850 --> 00:10:09.390
But a cloud of dust rose
beneath its hooves, and the feet

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:10.800
of the men right behind.

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:12.100
it.

00:10:12.100 --> 00:10:15.570
The pig is chased instead
of just being tied down

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:18.050
and butchered to save its blood.

00:10:18.050 --> 00:10:20.250
The blood is what
makes it tasty.

00:10:20.250 --> 00:10:24.700
The idea is to scare the
pig with screams and cries

00:10:24.700 --> 00:10:26.700
and make it run for its life

00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:30.470
until it collapses
from exhaustion.

00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:33.120
In Sankarapardu[Phonetic]
that morning, young women

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:36.970
and girls admired the muscles
rippling beneath the men's

00:10:36.970 --> 00:10:40.360
glistening brown skin as
they wielded their sticks.

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:43.790
The women's eyes ran all over
the hunter's bodies taking

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:47.600
in the smalls of their backs,
their thighs, their chests,

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:51.360
their narrow waists, the
lips that held their cigars.

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:55.220
Each thought fondly
of her own man --

00:10:55.220 --> 00:11:00.240
each thought fondly how her own
man ran faster than the rest,

00:11:00.240 --> 00:11:03.590
how he tackled the pick
expertly to the ground.

00:11:03.590 --> 00:11:06.520
The men were aware the
women were watching,

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:10.930
and they tried their
hardest to impress them.

00:11:10.930 --> 00:11:15.180
The pig ran and ran for half an
hour until it could run no more,

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:17.430
and finally it dropped
to the ground.

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:20.210
One hunter threw his
special net over it,

00:11:20.210 --> 00:11:21.980
and the others raised
their sticks

00:11:21.980 --> 00:11:25.280
and beat the animal
half conscious.

00:11:25.280 --> 00:11:27.570
They carried it to the
center of the village,

00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:31.140
and tied its snout shut
with a roop -- a rope.

00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:33.380
They tied its front
legs to a pole

00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:35.830
and stood it up on
its hind legs.

00:11:35.830 --> 00:11:40.220
The dazed pig looked
up at the sky.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:44.600
As a piglet grows in size,
its neck gets soon so fat

00:11:44.600 --> 00:11:47.830
that as long as it
lives, it is never able

00:11:47.830 --> 00:11:50.830
to lift its head
and look at the sky.

00:11:50.830 --> 00:11:53.540
But a wedding pig
in the last moments

00:11:53.540 --> 00:11:56.580
of its life gazes
skyward at last

00:11:56.580 --> 00:11:59.680
for the first time
and the last time.

00:11:59.680 --> 00:12:02.970
Untouchables will say,
untouchable man who has lived

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:06.330
in poverty all his life,
never having had a moment

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:10.280
of happiness, but for a
small respect at the end

00:12:10.280 --> 00:12:13.420
when his son gets a
job and is finally able

00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:15.510
to take care of his parents.

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:18.500
[ Foreign Language Spoken ]

00:12:20.100 --> 00:12:23.570
Sujatha Gidla: This fellow
is like a pig, he saw the sky

00:12:23.570 --> 00:12:26.800
for the first time at
the end of his life.

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:29.400
On that wedding morning,
the man responsible

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:32.690
for preparing the pig gently
roasted the still living pig,

00:12:32.690 --> 00:12:35.760
and carried it to
the bride's house.

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:40.020
For lack of cutting board, they
unhinged the front door of --

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:41.700
and laid the pig on it.

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:43.350
Two elders, Uncle
Malayo[Phonetic]

00:12:43.350 --> 00:12:45.730
and cousin Abednego were invited

00:12:45.730 --> 00:12:48.430
to do the honors
and carve the pig.

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:51.830
A few years before,
a Brahmin in Gurdwara

00:12:51.830 --> 00:12:54.660
who worshiped Gandhi had
spread the principles

00:12:54.660 --> 00:12:59.050
of nonviolence among all in
Sunri, especially the cruel

00:12:59.050 --> 00:13:01.230
and crude untouchables.

00:13:01.230 --> 00:13:04.420
One day, he found himself
in an untouchable colony

00:13:04.420 --> 00:13:06.930
where a feast was taking place.

00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:09.980
Before the men could
lay the pig on the door,

00:13:09.980 --> 00:13:13.220
the Brahmin pushed his way
forward and laid himself

00:13:13.220 --> 00:13:15.650
down in the pig's place.

00:13:15.650 --> 00:13:18.080
He wept, "How can anyone

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:20.880
with a heart hurt
this voiceless animal?

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:22.250
Are you not human?

00:13:22.250 --> 00:13:25.780
Haven't you heard the teachings
of our great spirit Gandhi?

00:13:25.780 --> 00:13:28.320
He pleaded with the
untouchables to cut himself

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:32.420
up before they take a knife
to that creation of Gods.

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:36.370
The youth in the colony full
drunk, pinned the Brahmin down

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:40.660
and held a knife to his throat
before their elders intervened.

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:45.520
The Brahmin scurried off
and never tried that again.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:48.850
Good thing he didn't stay
to watch what they did next.

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:52.080
If he had, he might
have fainted.

00:13:52.080 --> 00:13:54.070
Majula herself couldn't
bare to watch

00:13:54.070 --> 00:13:58.840
as the wedding cook
separated out the intestines

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:01.140
which would make
it salty sauteed.

00:14:01.140 --> 00:14:03.830
Other special parts
were carefully removed.

00:14:03.830 --> 00:14:06.380
The heart, the brain,
and the liver.

00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:10.690
A curry made out of these
is not meant for everyone.

00:14:10.690 --> 00:14:14.780
A portion of it is given to the
pastor who performs the wedding,

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:17.800
and the rest goes to
the wedding families.

00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:21.510
For days the pig would
feed the whole colony.

00:14:21.510 --> 00:14:24.320
They'd make soup with
its bones and curries

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:26.980
out of its hooves and testicles.

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:29.400
People would swear
how diviine it is

00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:31.950
to eat pork fried
while drinking.

00:14:31.950 --> 00:14:35.090
"Chicken is nothing"
they would say.

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:38.710
But the affair of the pig
is more than its taste.

00:14:38.710 --> 00:14:42.580
It's the circus of hunting
it, the feats of the men.

00:14:42.580 --> 00:14:47.150
The heroic -- it's heroic,
it's romantic, it's erotic.

00:14:47.150 --> 00:14:51.700
It's a metaphor, it's rhetoric,
it is deeply philosophical.

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:54.570
But these are all
mere super structures,

00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:58.150
at the base it's economic.

00:14:58.150 --> 00:15:00.730
The cheapest meat for the
cheapest man on earth."

