So, there was a dissident
group --

00:26:52.860 --> 00:26:55.740
descent group who
broke off from it.

00:26:55.740 --> 00:26:58.740
And they were inspired
by the revolution

00:26:58.740 --> 00:27:02.380
in China 1949 under Mao.

00:27:02.380 --> 00:27:05.600
And it's the Maoist struggle
that he was attracted to,

00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:09.700
and he went on to found
the Maoist movement

00:27:09.700 --> 00:27:15.250
that now India calls the
most dangerous, you know,

00:27:15.250 --> 00:27:17.950
security threat in India.

00:27:17.950 --> 00:27:20.660
That -- he was one of the
founders of the thing, and --

00:27:20.660 --> 00:27:22.370
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: And that's
an ongoing political struggle

00:27:22.370 --> 00:27:23.670
in India.

00:27:23.670 --> 00:27:24.970
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla:
On going, yeah.

00:27:24.970 --> 00:27:26.270
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: The
Naxalites movement.

00:27:26.270 --> 00:27:27.570
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:27:27.570 --> 00:27:29.640
Like, in the tribal areas, the
big mining companies are trying

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:33.840
to grab the land of tribals and
kick them out of the forests.

00:27:33.840 --> 00:27:37.430
So, he died, but his
legacy still lives

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:40.980
on even though he was
even expelled from it.

00:27:40.980 --> 00:27:45.170
So, it -- in that sense, he
wanted to take his destination

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:49.490
and his peoples' destination
in his own hands, and you know?

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:50.810
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Was that
something that you knew

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:52.110
about when you were a girl?

00:27:52.110 --> 00:27:53.720
Did you have -- did
you understand

00:27:53.720 --> 00:27:55.470
that your uncle was this man?

00:27:55.470 --> 00:27:59.810
Or was it -- was that kept from
you because you were a child?

00:27:59.810 --> 00:28:02.090
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: When I
was five years old he went

00:28:02.090 --> 00:28:05.650
underground, he disappeared
from public life,

00:28:05.650 --> 00:28:07.720
went to live in the forest.

00:28:07.720 --> 00:28:10.320
And we learned about him only

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:12.990
through the stories
of my mother.

00:28:12.990 --> 00:28:15.050
She would say, "That
your uncle went off

00:28:15.050 --> 00:28:16.620
to fight for the poor people.

00:28:16.620 --> 00:28:22.060
He lives in the jungle, and
he has guns and all that stuff

00:28:22.060 --> 00:28:24.910
to fight the rich
people, take their money

00:28:24.910 --> 00:28:27.540
and distribute among
the poor people.

00:28:27.540 --> 00:28:28.850
That's the kind of story --

00:28:28.850 --> 00:28:30.150
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: He's
like Robinhood.

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:31.450
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla:
Robinson, right.

00:28:31.450 --> 00:28:32.750
.

00:28:32.750 --> 00:28:34.050
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Yeah.

00:28:34.050 --> 00:28:35.350
Yeah.

00:28:35.350 --> 00:28:36.650
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:28:36.650 --> 00:28:37.950
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: And --

00:28:37.950 --> 00:28:39.250
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: So, obviously,
I was very inspired by that.

00:28:39.250 --> 00:28:40.550
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Right.

00:28:40.550 --> 00:28:41.850
So, I was going to -- I --

00:28:41.850 --> 00:28:43.150
one of the most chilling
components comes toward the end

00:28:43.150 --> 00:28:44.450
when you kind of
-- and I don't want

00:28:44.450 --> 00:28:46.540
to spoil exactly what happens,
but, you shed some context

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:52.450
in the ways in which even this
Maoist struggle that seems to be

00:28:52.450 --> 00:28:55.890
so idealistic, was
actually still riven

00:28:55.890 --> 00:28:57.250
with these caste tensions.

00:28:57.250 --> 00:28:58.550
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:28:58.550 --> 00:28:59.850
Yeah.

00:28:59.850 --> 00:29:01.150
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alma: And
that your uncle,

00:29:01.150 --> 00:29:05.340
who was an untouchable man and
has this, really utopian ideal

00:29:05.340 --> 00:29:06.970
that all men are created equal.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:08.270
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:09.570
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alma: Even
he was betrayed

00:29:09.570 --> 00:29:10.870
by the people that he led --

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:12.170
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:29:12.170 --> 00:29:13.470
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alma: That the
movement didn't really live

00:29:13.470 --> 00:29:14.770
up to that particular standard.

00:29:14.770 --> 00:29:16.070
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:29:16.070 --> 00:29:17.370
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alma: And
you close the book,

00:29:17.370 --> 00:29:19.590
you do this really charming
thing of introducing yourself

00:29:19.590 --> 00:29:22.060
as a baby at the end of
the book, and then you kind

00:29:22.060 --> 00:29:23.520
of close the book
talking a little bit

00:29:23.520 --> 00:29:25.350
about yourself as an adult.

00:29:25.350 --> 00:29:27.800
And I'm curious,
whether you see yourself

00:29:27.800 --> 00:29:31.480
as having inherited your uncle's
mantle of political activism?

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:34.460
and thinking about poverty,
and difference, and class,

00:29:34.460 --> 00:29:36.970
and how we do that in this
country as opposed to India?

00:29:36.970 --> 00:29:38.270
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Oh, yeah.

00:29:38.270 --> 00:29:39.570
Definitely.

00:29:39.570 --> 00:29:42.320
My uncle was the most
influential person in my life.

00:29:42.320 --> 00:29:47.000
And at 14, actually I wanted
to become a guerrilla like him.

00:29:47.000 --> 00:29:51.270
And it -- it was -- and I think
it was at 19 before I took

00:29:51.270 --> 00:29:55.430
up rifle and ran off to forest,
I was arrested and tortured.

00:29:55.430 --> 00:30:02.090
So, that never happened, but --
and also, as I came to America,

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:05.310
and there's like, more
resources to read for yourself.

00:30:05.310 --> 00:30:09.530
And I read, you know, these
movements by myself instead

00:30:09.530 --> 00:30:11.590
of getting indoctrinated.

00:30:11.590 --> 00:30:15.160
And I disagreed with
his political program

00:30:15.160 --> 00:30:19.220
and tactics before he was
expelled from the party

00:30:19.220 --> 00:30:22.510
that he himself founded,
and even after.

00:30:22.510 --> 00:30:28.900
But the main aim that, you know,
there should be equality, like,

00:30:28.900 --> 00:30:31.760
equal access to everybody
to all resources

00:30:31.760 --> 00:30:33.750
that is still my ideal.

00:30:33.750 --> 00:30:36.570
And that problem is not
limited to untouchables

00:30:36.570 --> 00:30:38.200
in India, but here as well --

00:30:38.200 --> 00:30:39.500
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Yeah.

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:40.800
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: You
know, the race question.

00:30:40.800 --> 00:30:44.640
And so, I don't see myself as
like, oh, I have to be in India

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:49.400
to fight against injustice, and
I can do this very well here.

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:56.490
And I am very passionate about,
you know, social struggles,

00:30:56.490 --> 00:30:59.250
anti racist struggles,
and I parcpated --

00:30:59.250 --> 00:31:01.980
I participate in them.

00:31:01.980 --> 00:31:03.530
And of course, I do...

00:31:03.530 --> 00:31:07.200
I still continue
his legacy of --

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:08.500
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Yeah.

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:10.140
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: You know, the
passion for social struggle.

00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:11.920
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: We're going
to open it up to questions,

00:31:11.920 --> 00:31:14.080
so if anyone has a question,
but I have another one,

00:31:14.080 --> 00:31:16.590
so while you guys are gathering
your thoughts or making your way

00:31:16.590 --> 00:31:19.750
to the microphone, I want to ask
you a little bit about the way

00:31:19.750 --> 00:31:21.960
in which you wrote this story.

00:31:21.960 --> 00:31:25.290
Because, you -- in the
section the Sujatha read,

00:31:25.290 --> 00:31:30.200
you could hear her reading
sort of close observations

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:31.920
and some scene setting.

00:31:31.920 --> 00:31:35.530
And in the New York Times
review by Michiko Kakutani,

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:38.010
she likened the work to Dickens.

00:31:38.010 --> 00:31:39.980
And I'm curious if
you can explain

00:31:39.980 --> 00:31:42.890
to us how you learned
these stories.

00:31:42.890 --> 00:31:45.270
And how you approached
writing them.

00:31:45.270 --> 00:31:47.470
You used dialogue and
all of these things

00:31:47.470 --> 00:31:49.450
that you couldn't had know,
because you weren't there.

00:31:49.450 --> 00:31:50.750
You weren't even
alive for so much

00:31:50.750 --> 00:31:52.050
of what you're writing about

00:31:52.050 --> 00:31:53.350
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:31:53.350 --> 00:31:54.650
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Tell
me a little bit

00:31:54.650 --> 00:31:59.530
about how you approached this
family's story, and how you,

00:31:59.530 --> 00:32:02.010
you know, the responsibility
of writing something

00:32:02.010 --> 00:32:04.110
that accurately -- accurately

00:32:04.110 --> 00:32:06.590
that you couldn't
know firsthand.

00:32:06.590 --> 00:32:08.420
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: I
was able to write.

00:32:08.420 --> 00:32:11.910
I was even able to think of
writing down something only

00:32:11.910 --> 00:32:14.690
because I left India
and I came to America.

00:32:14.690 --> 00:32:18.060
It's because, talking
about caste is taboo.

00:32:18.060 --> 00:32:20.130
The upper caste people
don't want to hear

00:32:20.130 --> 00:32:22.550
that there is still
caste system in India.

00:32:22.550 --> 00:32:24.800
And lower caste people
like myself,

00:32:24.800 --> 00:32:27.140
we are too ashamed
to talk about it.

00:32:27.140 --> 00:32:28.830
We are too ashamed to inquire

00:32:28.830 --> 00:32:31.810
into it why it happened
like that.

00:32:31.810 --> 00:32:34.740
And I came here, and I
came here during the Iraq

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:36.840
war demonstrations.

00:32:36.840 --> 00:32:39.990
And I saw at least
some White people

00:32:39.990 --> 00:32:43.930
if not all White people
being anti racist,

00:32:43.930 --> 00:32:48.610
and not just being anti racist,
but passionately anti racist.

00:32:48.610 --> 00:32:52.280
That could never had
been imagined in India

00:32:52.280 --> 00:32:54.690
with untouchables
and caste Hindus.

00:32:54.690 --> 00:33:01.070
And so, if people are okay with
you know, people of other race

00:33:01.070 --> 00:33:04.530
and it's not shame to
be a different race,

00:33:04.530 --> 00:33:06.080
why can't I be like that?

00:33:06.080 --> 00:33:10.630
Why should I be ashamed of
being born an untouchable?

00:33:10.630 --> 00:33:12.480
So, that's when I
started inquiring,

00:33:12.480 --> 00:33:14.580
why did I become an untouchable?

00:33:14.580 --> 00:33:19.680
And so, I would talk
to different people,

00:33:19.680 --> 00:33:22.760
but I thought the best source
would be to call my mother

00:33:22.760 --> 00:33:26.960
and ask her, do you know
why we became untouchables?

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:33.150
And so, she started telling
the story of my ancestors,

00:33:33.150 --> 00:33:37.110
that is her great grandfather.

00:33:37.110 --> 00:33:40.330
And it's only since then
that she knew the story of.

00:33:40.330 --> 00:33:42.460
And when she was
telling the story,

00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:46.030
I was able to realize how
they became untouchables.

00:33:46.030 --> 00:33:49.720
And so, while I started
this story to --

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:51.710
as an inquiring to
finding out caste,

00:33:51.710 --> 00:33:55.400
but their stories themselves
I found very interesting.

00:33:55.400 --> 00:33:57.620
And she asked me to
talk to my uncle,

00:33:57.620 --> 00:34:00.070
and my uncle led
a very colorful,

00:34:00.070 --> 00:34:02.680
adventurous charismatic life.

00:34:02.680 --> 00:34:03.980
And --

00:34:03.980 --> 00:34:05.280
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: That
is an understatement.

00:34:05.280 --> 00:34:06.580
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:34:06.580 --> 00:34:07.880
Yeah.

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:09.180
&gt;&gt; Ranmaan Alam: That
is an un -- I mean --

00:34:09.180 --> 00:34:10.480
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:34:10.480 --> 00:34:11.780
&gt;&gt; Ranmaan: Your uncle,
like, the things that he --

00:34:11.780 --> 00:34:13.080
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:34:13.080 --> 00:34:14.380
&gt;&gt; Ranmaan Gidla: The stories
that are relayed in his book,

00:34:14.380 --> 00:34:15.680
and they have this quality
of -- it's almost like --

00:34:15.680 --> 00:34:17.220
it's almost like the reader
gets to be on the telephone

00:34:17.220 --> 00:34:18.540
and your uncle, do
you know what I mean?

00:34:18.540 --> 00:34:19.840
It was like you're hearing --

00:34:19.840 --> 00:34:21.140
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Oh!

00:34:21.140 --> 00:34:22.440
Actually, a lot of this
interviewing is done

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:23.740
through the phone.

00:34:23.740 --> 00:34:25.040
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: And
you can feel that.

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:26.340
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:34:26.340 --> 00:34:27.640
Yeah.

00:34:27.640 --> 00:34:28.940
&gt;&gt; Rumaan: Alam: I think
we have a question here.

00:34:28.940 --> 00:34:30.240
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah, sorry.

00:34:30.240 --> 00:34:31.540
&gt;&gt; I understand that
the constitution

00:34:31.540 --> 00:34:34.840
of India reserves some
degree of political strength

00:34:34.840 --> 00:34:39.430
to various castes by assured
proportions in the legislator.

00:34:39.430 --> 00:34:41.810
I -- it at least originally did.

00:34:41.810 --> 00:34:45.330
But, is there a campaign by
the government or otherwise

00:34:45.330 --> 00:34:48.450
to destroy the concept of caste?

00:34:48.450 --> 00:34:52.350
To say, there are no difference,
that people are not predestined?

00:34:52.350 --> 00:34:57.800
Essentially, is there any
acceptance of that as a concept

00:34:57.800 --> 00:35:00.830
that the caste serves
no real purpose?

00:35:00.830 --> 00:35:03.750
That it's a real --
it's a false concept?

00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:05.960
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Actually,
I would disagree with you.

00:35:05.960 --> 00:35:11.130
Caste has a real purpose, it has
a real material basis for it.

00:35:11.130 --> 00:35:12.430
&gt;&gt; It --

00:35:12.430 --> 00:35:14.540
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Because there
are certain classes of people,

00:35:14.540 --> 00:35:17.600
a very tiny minority
of people benefit

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:21.010
from perpetuating this system.

00:35:21.010 --> 00:35:22.310
&gt;&gt; It has no biologic basis.

00:35:22.310 --> 00:35:23.610
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:35:23.610 --> 00:35:24.910
Yeah.

00:35:24.910 --> 00:35:26.210
&gt;&gt; It serves economics.

00:35:26.210 --> 00:35:27.510
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:35:27.510 --> 00:35:30.530
And the second thing is, in 1915
they have made untouchability a

00:35:30.530 --> 00:35:32.300
ille -- a crime.

00:35:32.300 --> 00:35:36.500
But, India has literally,
thousands of rules

00:35:36.500 --> 00:35:38.470
against caste discrimination,

00:35:38.470 --> 00:35:42.750
but none of them
is ever respected.

00:35:42.750 --> 00:35:47.500
Just like here there is
no right or Black man

00:35:47.500 --> 00:35:50.750
that White man is -- what is is?

00:35:50.750 --> 00:35:53.740
Is obliged to respect, yeah.

00:35:53.740 --> 00:35:55.040
&gt;&gt; Is equal.

00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:56.340
It's, well --

00:35:56.340 --> 00:35:57.640
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:35:57.640 --> 00:35:58.940
&gt;&gt; Our system would
say equal justice.

00:35:58.940 --> 00:36:01.760
Is there a notion civically
and endorsed publically

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:04.860
that these considerations
just don't exist

00:36:04.860 --> 00:36:06.160
and ought to be ignored?

00:36:06.160 --> 00:36:08.540
Is there a popular
support for that?

00:36:08.540 --> 00:36:09.840
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: A
popular support -- ?

00:36:09.840 --> 00:36:12.080
&gt;&gt; In India for doing
away with the concept.

00:36:12.080 --> 00:36:13.520
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:14.820
I mean --

00:36:14.820 --> 00:36:16.270
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Like,
politically is there any kind

00:36:16.270 --> 00:36:21.920
of movement in the country to
move past the system to sort

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:25.910
of legalize -- legally say this
should not be the way it is?

00:36:25.910 --> 00:36:29.260
Or you're saying -- or are you
saying that there are laws,

00:36:29.260 --> 00:36:32.040
but socially they're
not enforced?

00:36:32.040 --> 00:36:33.340
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:36:33.340 --> 00:36:37.650
So, there's no point in fighting
for more laws and more you know,

00:36:37.650 --> 00:36:42.970
these things, because the
laws are simply not followed.

00:36:42.970 --> 00:36:47.410
So, the only way
to fight for it is

00:36:47.410 --> 00:36:50.510
to destroy the economic
structures

00:36:50.510 --> 00:36:53.520
that necessitate the
perpetuation of caste.

00:36:53.520 --> 00:36:57.160
For example, in rural
India, landlords own castes

00:36:57.160 --> 00:36:59.510
and they need laborers
to work for it.

00:36:59.510 --> 00:37:04.550
And they need laborers copiously
and reliably all the time.

00:37:04.550 --> 00:37:08.660
So, they don't want these people
to go to city and get educated

00:37:08.660 --> 00:37:10.210
and become a doctor or a lawyer.

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:12.270
They want to keep these people,

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:15.350
a reserve of people
to work on the land.

00:37:15.350 --> 00:37:18.110
That is the material
basis of caste.

00:37:18.110 --> 00:37:22.450
Caste is not like some evil idea
or something, it has a root,

00:37:22.450 --> 00:37:24.550
economic root in it, you know?

00:37:24.550 --> 00:37:27.590
And so, unless those
structures are demolished,

00:37:27.590 --> 00:37:30.710
there's really no hope for you
know, abolishment of caste.

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:32.010
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: Right.

00:37:32.010 --> 00:37:33.310
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:37:33.310 --> 00:37:34.610
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: We
have another questions.

00:37:34.610 --> 00:37:35.910
&gt;&gt; Hi. I have two questions.

00:37:35.910 --> 00:37:37.650
One is, where did
you learn to read?

00:37:37.650 --> 00:37:41.540
I didn't know that India
educates untouchables.

00:37:41.540 --> 00:37:44.940
And the second is, how did
you get to America, like,

00:37:44.940 --> 00:37:46.240
how did you get the money?

00:37:46.240 --> 00:37:47.540
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yes, okay.

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:48.840
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:37:48.840 --> 00:37:50.330
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: But,
you know, I say this --

00:37:50.330 --> 00:37:53.100
one time I said this to
the interviewer like,

00:37:53.100 --> 00:37:56.720
how did you become like one
of these two persons of --

00:37:56.720 --> 00:37:59.400
untouchables that escaped it?

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:03.610
I think that historically,
the green lights kept popping

00:38:03.610 --> 00:38:06.340
up just in time for
us, you know?

00:38:06.340 --> 00:38:10.280
Like, my great grandmother
was there in the --

00:38:10.280 --> 00:38:14.370
Canadian White missionaries
came to India, and they wanted

00:38:14.370 --> 00:38:16.010
to convert people
to Christianity.

00:38:16.010 --> 00:38:19.180
But, castes Hindus didn't want
to convert because they thought

00:38:19.180 --> 00:38:21.650
that they would lose
their caste status.

00:38:21.650 --> 00:38:24.650
The only people left to
convert were untouchables.

00:38:24.650 --> 00:38:28.620
And untouchables in droves
took Christianity in India.

00:38:28.620 --> 00:38:31.560
And because they took
Christianity, I mean,

00:38:31.560 --> 00:38:34.430
even otherwise they would
have been, they were allowed

00:38:34.430 --> 00:38:35.850
into Christian schools,

00:38:35.850 --> 00:38:38.020
missionary schools
to get education.

00:38:38.020 --> 00:38:40.270
They were allowed into
missionary hospitals

00:38:40.270 --> 00:38:42.850
to get treatment for their
children and their ailing.

00:38:42.850 --> 00:38:46.290
And that's a historical
opportunity that happened just

00:38:46.290 --> 00:38:48.230
in time for my great
grandparents.

00:38:48.230 --> 00:38:51.870
And the second generation
was independence.

00:38:51.870 --> 00:38:55.690
Immediately after independence,
there's this hunky dory feeling

00:38:55.690 --> 00:38:59.690
of "Oh, we defeated the
foreigner and we're all one."

00:38:59.690 --> 00:39:04.210
And so, people, some people
like, you know, believe it.

00:39:04.210 --> 00:39:07.280
And so, were treating
other people like, equally.

00:39:07.280 --> 00:39:11.460
And it is during that time that
my mother and father were able

00:39:11.460 --> 00:39:13.510
to go to school and
get education.

00:39:13.510 --> 00:39:17.500
And those institution's
garment schools persisted

00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:19.140
until my generation.

00:39:19.140 --> 00:39:21.070
And they're destroyed
after that,

00:39:21.070 --> 00:39:25.680
now untouchables have very
little chance of advancement.

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:26.980
And -- ?

00:39:26.980 --> 00:39:28.280
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: And
so, how did you come

00:39:28.280 --> 00:39:29.580
to live in the United States?

00:39:29.580 --> 00:39:31.170
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: I -- so,
as I said, my grandparents,

00:39:31.170 --> 00:39:32.870
missionary educated, and after

00:39:32.870 --> 00:39:35.500
that my parents in
garment colleges.

00:39:35.500 --> 00:39:38.690
And I also was able
to go to school.

00:39:38.690 --> 00:39:42.870
And I went to this institution
called IIT, the Institute

00:39:42.870 --> 00:39:46.110
of Technology, it's
sort of like MIT.

00:39:46.110 --> 00:39:50.320
There, the trajectory of
students over there is

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:52.910
in final year take GREs
and [inaudible] to get

00:39:52.910 --> 00:39:56.440
out of this country, and go
to the first world country.

00:39:56.440 --> 00:39:58.960
So, I happened to be
in that environment

00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:01.780
and I just followed what
other people were doing,

00:40:01.780 --> 00:40:03.080
and that's how I came here.

00:40:03.080 --> 00:40:07.150
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: I think we
had another question here.

00:40:07.150 --> 00:40:13.240
&gt;&gt; You talked about the economic
supports of the caste system.

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:15.750
Is there a religious
support to it?

00:40:15.750 --> 00:40:18.870
And I don't know if these
thoughts are at all correct,

00:40:18.870 --> 00:40:23.300
but I'm thinking, karma
and reincarnation.

00:40:23.300 --> 00:40:26.060
Are there religious
ties to the system?

00:40:26.060 --> 00:40:30.370
And are there difference among
the different religious peoples

00:40:30.370 --> 00:40:33.740
in India in their approach
to the caste system?

00:40:33.740 --> 00:40:36.100
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Oh,
you know, people think

00:40:36.100 --> 00:40:39.520
that caste is associated
with Hinduism.

00:40:39.520 --> 00:40:42.120
The basis for it is, Hindu is --

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:48.080
has a creator Lord Brahma
is -- was the creator.

00:40:48.080 --> 00:40:51.870
He created humans
to fall into one

00:40:51.870 --> 00:40:55.240
of the four casts
or as an outcast.

00:40:55.240 --> 00:40:59.440
So, it says in Hindu text
that the Brahmin comes

00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:04.140
from the forehead of the
ceater, the -- Lord Brahma.

00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:08.110
And the Kshatriyas , the warrior
caste comes from the shoulders,

00:41:08.110 --> 00:41:10.130
the arms of the creator.

00:41:10.130 --> 00:41:15.030
And the Vaishyas, the merchant
caste comes from you know.

00:41:15.030 --> 00:41:17.830
And the service caste, potters.

00:41:17.830 --> 00:41:19.900
prostitutes, diggers,
carpenters,

00:41:19.900 --> 00:41:23.060
they come from the
legs of the Brahma.

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:27.090
So, it's also is -- the
occupation is assoc --

00:41:27.090 --> 00:41:28.870
[inaudible] with the
religious purity.

00:41:28.870 --> 00:41:31.790
And so, Brahmins are
the purest people.

00:41:31.790 --> 00:41:35.960
And the untouchables
come un-sanctioned

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:39.900
by Lord Brahma beneath his feet,

00:41:39.900 --> 00:41:41.700
and that's why they're
the most impure.

00:41:41.700 --> 00:41:47.880
So, Hinduism is basically a
religious prop for caste system.

00:41:47.880 --> 00:41:50.050
It justifies caste system,

00:41:50.050 --> 00:41:54.260
it gives religious
sanction for caste system.

00:41:54.260 --> 00:41:58.040
I think if I'm not
incorrect, Confucian --

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:03.250
Confucianism is also a
philosophy that's, you know,

00:42:03.250 --> 00:42:06.150
invented for social
structuring of people.

00:42:06.150 --> 00:42:08.910
So, it has religious purpose,

00:42:08.910 --> 00:42:13.390
but Indian society is
what necessitates caste.

00:42:13.390 --> 00:42:16.880
So, even other religious people
coming to India they fall

00:42:16.880 --> 00:42:18.370
into one caste or the other.

00:42:18.370 --> 00:42:21.400
So, Islam, they're
Indian Muslims have caste.

00:42:21.400 --> 00:42:23.020
Muslims outside don't
have caste,

00:42:23.020 --> 00:42:24.800
but Indian Muslims have caste.

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:26.830
Christians don't have
caste, they don't even know

00:42:26.830 --> 00:42:31.500
about caste, but in India,
Christians have caste.

00:42:31.500 --> 00:42:32.800
&gt;&gt; Rumaan Alam: You
had a question.

00:42:32.800 --> 00:42:35.890
&gt;&gt; Yeah. So, you said that to
dismantle the caste system you

00:42:35.890 --> 00:42:38.150
have to attack the
economic structure

00:42:38.150 --> 00:42:39.600
that is propping it up?

00:42:39.600 --> 00:42:40.900
&gt;&gt; Sujatha Gidla: Yeah.

00:42:40.900 --> 00:42:45.170
&gt;&gt; So -- but, that's an idea,
but to actually implement it,

00:42:45.170 --> 00:42:47.580
will you say that it's --

00:42:47.580 --> 00:42:49.590
it should be through the
political system like,

00:42:49.590 --> 00:42:52.300
affirmative action, or if it
has been there for some time?

00:42:52.300 --> 00:42:55.120
Or through people's movement
that are slowly coming up

00:42:55.120 --> 00:42:58.860
and gaining steam in India?

